    <text>
        <body>
            <head>72. Memorandum From the Executive Secretary of the Department of State (<persName
                    corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">Tarnoff</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for
                National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu"
                    >Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d72fn1"
                    >Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country
                    File, Box 3, Algeria: 1/77–11/80. Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1979-02-10"
                        >February 10, 1979</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Initiatives Toward <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <list type="references">
                <head>REF</head>
                <item>
                    <persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName> to Secretary
                    Memorandum of January 9<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d72fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d70">Document 70</ref>.</note>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Attached is a list of phased initiatives which the <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> and other interested agencies
                are considering with a view toward strengthening U.S. <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> with post-<persName
                    corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName>
                <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>, where a new President
                was elected on February 7 and inaugurated on February 9.</p>
            <p>Implementation of many of these initiatives will be contingent on the new regime’s
                attitude toward the U.S. We also will take into account their effect on our
                relations with other states in the region. We will coordinate closely with the
                    <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName> as we
                proceed.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Peter Tarnoff</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d72fn3">
                        <persName corresp="recGMHYY5eBNFZMVt">Perry</persName> signed for <persName
                            corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">Tarnoff</persName>.</note>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Executive Secretary</hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
            <frus:attachment xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
                <note>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Attachment</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Paper Prepared in the <orgName
                            corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d72fn4">Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1979-02-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                            notBefore="1979-02-09T00:00:00-05:00">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rendition="simple_centre">
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Initiatives to Strengthen U.S.-<placeName
                            corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                        <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">Relations</rs>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <p rendition="simple_left">PROSPECTIVE ACTIONS DURING NEXT 3 MONTHS:</p>
                <p>—Send a high-level delegation, including <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                        >Congressional</orgName> representation, to <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> early in the administration
                    of <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> President
                        <persName corresp="rec3K7qfHncylhCkn">Bendjedid</persName>, perhaps when his
                    new government is selected and con<pb facs="0209" n="188" xml:id="pg_188"
                    />firmed by the Popular National Assembly. The <orgName
                        corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> has suggested a list of
                    names from which an eventual delegation can be drawn.</p>
                <p>—Send a letter from President <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                        >Carter</persName> to President <persName corresp="rec3K7qfHncylhCkn"
                        >Bendjedid</persName> encouraging continued close economic <rs
                        type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> and
                    political dialogue and inviting him to visit the U.S. at a mutually acceptable
                    future date. The <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> has
                    dispatched this letter to <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algeria</placeName>.</p>
                <p>—Respond to <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>’s desire
                    to increase the price of <rs type="topic" corresp="recKUoZhneLNlznJL">gas</rs>
                    under the El Paso I contract in a fashion which protects the interests of U.S.
                    consumers and minimizes disturbance to U.S.-<placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                    <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs>. The
                        <orgName corresp="recYUMjnpvSPEp5vc">Department of Energy</orgName> is
                    considering available options in consultation with <orgName
                        corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName>.</p>
                <p>—Offer <gloss target="#t_ICA_1">
                        <orgName corresp="rec6btFUJJcsbOTOq">ICA</orgName>
                    </gloss> travel grants enabling lecturers from New York University to instruct
                    at the <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> National
                    School of Administration (ENA). <gloss target="#t_ICA_1">
                        <orgName corresp="rec6btFUJJcsbOTOq">ICA</orgName>
                    </gloss> will be able to meet this request.</p>
                <p>—Encourage the new <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                    Government to sign a pending cultural agreement.</p>
                <p>—Identify funding available to carry out <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recjcAQL1g5hKP7b4">cultural exchange</rs> activities under the
                    prospective cultural agreement. These would include facilitating cooperative
                    relationships between American and <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algerian</placeName> universities. There is a possibility of using funds
                    under Section 661 of the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate"
                        corresp="recQ7wNs9H53qbIlS">Foreign Assistance Act</rs> for these
                    purposes.</p>
                <p>—Arrange consultations/briefings with the <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algerian</placeName> Foreign Minister on <placeName
                        corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> and African issues.</p>
                <p rendition="simple_left">PROSPECTIVE ACTIONS WITHIN 3 TO 9 MONTHS:</p>
                <p>—A visit to <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> by a <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="rec2DHm7M6y3nExAB">science and technology</rs> team,
                    perhaps headed by White House Science Advisor <persName
                        corresp="recwI5xqYuJhUK3w8">Frank Press</persName>, to encourage wider
                    cooperation in these areas. The <orgName corresp="recA3aXdY9naaZywc">National
                        Science Foundation</orgName> is prepared to send a team to <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> to consider specific forms
                    of cooperation.</p>
                <p>—A visit to <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> by
                    Secretary <persName corresp="reccnQOrpVU26Y2cT">Bergland</persName> to discuss
                        <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recUsSXH96nnonu86">agricultural development</rs> and
                    cooperation in sectors identified in a <gloss target="#t_USDA_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reczTng76kkvwxPlW">USDA</orgName>
                    </gloss>/<gloss target="#t_AID_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recQ4g5dcD4dLt6Es">AID</orgName>
                    </gloss> study where U.S. reimbursable technical assistance might be relevant to
                        <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> efforts.
                    Preliminary reactions from <gloss target="#t_USDA_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reczTng76kkvwxPlW">USDA</orgName>
                    </gloss> are that the Secretary would be interested in such a visit, possibly in
                    the summer.</p>
                <p>—Offer to consider modest amounts of <orgName corresp="reclzjV0td1de35mW"
                        >Eximbank</orgName> financing for equipment to be used in well-planned pilot
                    agricultural projects as a further indication of U.S. interest in <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recUsSXH96nnonu86">agricultural development</rs>.
                    Several of the agricultural projects in the <gloss target="#t_USDA_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reczTng76kkvwxPlW">USDA</orgName>
                    </gloss>/<gloss target="#t_AID_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recQ4g5dcD4dLt6Es">AID</orgName>
                    </gloss> study are suitable for such supplier credit financing.</p>
                <p>—Invite the commander of the <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algerian</placeName> Air Academy to visit the <orgName
                        corresp="recQqyaWRInyvoNwW">U.S. Air Force</orgName> Academy at Colorado
                    Springs. He has expressed interest <pb facs="0210" n="189" xml:id="pg_189"/> in
                    such a trip. The Air Force has indicated agreement in principle to such a
                        visit.<note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d72fn5">See <ref target="#d70fn2"
                            >footnote 2, Document 70</ref>.</note> If it is successful, invitations
                    could be extended to other <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algerian</placeName> service school chiefs.</p>
                <p>—Offer to assign a defense attache to Algiers. Defense agrees in principle.</p>
                <p>—Explore possibility of negotiating an <orgName corresp="recdxRpnn7TCTU0He"
                        >Overseas Private Investment Corporation</orgName> agreement with <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> to facilitate American
                    business in <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>. Embassy
                    Algiers has been asked to comment on this initiative.</p>
                <p>—Exchange visits of military students. <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                        >Algeria</placeName> received students from our National War College in
                    1977, and we could invite a comparable group to visit the U.S.</p>
                <p>—Subject to the state of our relations with both <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> and <placeName
                        corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>, we would consider early in
                    the summer of 1979 approaching the Algerians to ask if they would be interested
                    in sending some of their military to the United States for training beginning in
                        <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1981. Defense agrees in principle.</p>
            </frus:attachment>
